{"author":{"id":"9de5b1921f44bed195b915f8bfd092acf7cebaf7b18fb58759458b08aa04836a"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1621297642,"nonce":"NLrRnD1rL1CqmaNondDoQmnj5xg=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWU4OTM4MTkxNTc=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3679","origin":"github"},"title":"Having access to aTRAM 2.0 would be nice","message":"I'm preparing to analyze shotgun genomic data for paralogs of functional genes using aTRAM 2.0 (automated target restricted assembly method). This program assembles genes from WGS reads, using a BLAST algorithm. It's most used for seeking orthologs, but the creator Julie Allen said it could be used for paralogs if the SPAdes assembler is selected. Therefore, I think many researchers exploring different questions in comparative genomics or phylogenomics would be happy to be able to use this tool in Galaxy.\n\nHere is the link for the publication about the first incarnation, but version 2.0 would be better.\n\nAllen JM, Boyd B, Nguyen NB, et al. (2017). Phylogenomics from whole genome sequences using aTRAM. Systematic Biology 66: 786–798. doi: [10.1093/sysbio/syw105](http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/sysbio/syw105)\n\nHere is Allen's [talk](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xe8Hq797LFI) about the new version and how it works.\n\nThanks in advance if this is at all possible!","files":null}]}